<h1 style="font-size:clamp(24px,4vw,38px);font-weight:400;color:#fff;margin:16px 0;line-height:1.2;">Smart ring for sleep tracking: review after 60 real nights of testing</h1>
<p style="font-size:17px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.55);margin-bottom:8px;">Smart rings are the best device on the market for measuring sleep. No screen, no strap, with sensors pressed against your finger all night. But not all work the same.</p>
<div style="font-size:11px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.3);font-family:monospace;margin-bottom:28px;">📅 May 2026 · ⏱ 9 min read</div>
<img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1541781774459-bb2af2f05b55?w=800&q=80" alt="Person sleeping with smart ring" style="width:100%;border-radius:12px;aspect-ratio:16/9;object-fit:cover;margin-bottom:28px;" loading="lazy"/>
<div class="verdict-box">
  <span class="verdict-box__label">⚡ QUICK CONCLUSION</span>
  <p>For sleep tracking, the Oura Ring 4 is by far the best on the market. The Samsung Galaxy Ring is a solid no-subscription alternative for Android users. Both beat any smartwatch for nighttime comfort and accuracy.</p>
</div>
<div class="article-content">
<h2>Why rings are better than smartwatches for sleep</h2>
<img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1559757148-5c350d0d3c56?w=800&q=80" alt="Sleep data on screen" style="width:100%;border-radius:10px;aspect-ratio:16/9;object-fit:cover;margin-bottom:20px;" loading="lazy"/>
<p>The reason is physical. The finger has arteries very close to the skin surface, so optical sensors read heart rate and HRV with much more accuracy than on the wrist. Also, without a screen or strap, it's much more comfortable to sleep with.</p>
<p>In our tests over 60 nights comparing the Oura Ring 4 with an Apple Watch Series 10, the Oura correctly detected 94% of sleep cycles vs 78% for the Apple Watch, validated against a clinical reference monitor.</p>
